bug.short_desc: [j2ee] Use of IResource.getLocalTimestamp for modification checking is invalid

long_desc.thetext: You cannot trust, especially on linux, IResource.getLocalTimestamp to return the appropriate value. Note that due to varying file system timing granularities, this value is not guaranteed to change every time the file is modified. For a more reliable indication of whether the file has changed, use getModificationStamp. We should be using getModificationStamp instead. This is seen in a number of places throughout WTP. This should be cleaned up as it will cause unexpected behaviour. J2EEComponentClasspathContainer PublishUtil TarFileExporter ModuleFile ComponentDeployable

FYI, see bug 119769 for a related issue from 1.0. getModificationStamp() cannot be used (by itself) in cases where a file might be deleted and recreated with different contents. One example of this is in the Java output folder, where regular resources are deleted and recopied from the source folder. In these cases, the modification stamp never changes.

FYI, the call to the ModuleFile constructor in ComponentDeployable can be cleaned up just by switching to the other constructor that doesn't take the time stamp as the last argument. This just pushes the timestamp code out of your plugin so that it is all handled through ModuleFile.

We have no control over what the osgi class loader does. What do you want me to do? The standard class loader doesn't have this problem.

Ignore the OSGi classloader. SWT loads the same DLL twice in loadLibrary. In two different locations. Seems like one place is enough to me?
One place is org.eclipse.swt.internal.win32.OS.<clinit>. The other is org.eclipse.swt.internal.Callback.<clinit>.
Why have loadLibrary calls at both places?

Moving back to SWT.
The stack traces just show the fact that System.loadLibrary is getting called twice for the same library. The Bundle ClassLoader is looking for the library twice. The second time it is asked to locate a library the Bundle ClassLoader will find the library in the bundle but then will detect that it is already extracted and will not re-extract the library. It then returns the path to the originally extracted library.
The VM then will attempt to load the library from path and will notice that it is already loaded and will do nothing. This would happen on "normal" classloaders also. I don't see the problem.
In 3.3 M3 the framework does cache the lib path answers, so if a library is asked for again on the same classloader then we just return the original path without looking for it in the bundles zip file. This was done to fix bug 156873, not for performance reasons. I assume checking if an already open zip file contains an entry is very quick anyway.
I guess SWT should answer why they call loadLibrary twice for the same library. Otherwise I would close as wontfix.

I was just puzzled why SWT would have two places where it loads a DLL. It just looks strange and I thought it would be something Steve would care about. If not, fine with me too.
OSGi has nothing to do with this bug (if it is one).

The library is loaded in two places because is contains the native code for call-out from the OS class and call-in for the Callback class. The callback class is shared on all platforms while the OS class is platform specific. This means we can't have a reference from one to the other without either adding a dependency we don't want or API we don't want. Another solution would be to have a tiny library only for callback (which we don't want). If the Callback class is touched before OS, then the natives need to be there. If the OS class is touched before callback, then it needs to be there.
The spec for loadLibrary() says, "If this method is called more than once with the same library name, the second and subsequent calls are ignored". We were relying on this. From the stack that Chris posted, it seemed that the library was being extracted from the zip twice and (possibly) loaded twice. Is that the case?

Actually, Chris said: "Both paths extract the DLL from the bundle jar, turn it into a file, and the call loadLibrary on it" which seemed really bad to me. If this is wrong, let's close this bug report.

The library is not being extracted twice or loaded twice. Instead the VM is asking the classloader to locate the library twice, there is a difference. The VM then does all the handling to detect wheather the library path (which was located by the classloader) has already been loaded.
Probaby should close as wontfix, the framework is not going to do anything for you here.
Works as designed. Thanks for following up, both Tom and Steve.

bug.short_desc: Change resource modification stamp when resource is recreated

long_desc.thetext:
In WTP server tools, I need to check when files have changed within the workspace, and use this to calculate deltas and publish changes out to a server. To do this, I need a reliable 'change stamp' for comparisons.
Based on bug 160718, getLocalTimeStamp() isn't always accurate on Linux and can't be used to check for file changes.
Based on bug 119769, getModificationStamp() isn't always accurate because it doesn't update when a file is deleted and replaced with new contents, such as regular files in a JDT output directory.
Is there a reliable stamp that I can use? Should I continue my current approach of adding both and hope that nobody tries to publish Java projects on Linux? Or should we use this as a bug in getModificationStamp()?

I think both methods are behaving as specified (getLocalTimeStamp even mentions the granularity problem), but I appreciate the dillemma. Of course the best way to detect if a resource has changed is via a resource change listener and check for the CONTENT flag. This will detect the delete+recreate case as well as normal content change.
We could strengthen the spec of IResource#getModificationStamp to say that we attempt to make it change across deletion/creation. We could implement this internally by using the nodeId as the initial value rather than 0. The nodeId is generated from a counter that is incremented every time a resource is created.

Resource change events are good in some situations, but I want to be able to tell if things have changed when my plugins weren't activated. There could be multiple resource change events and restarts between publishes too, so I'd also have to keep incrementing and saving the information when I don't need it yet.
Just using a counter internally would be a huge improvement for me, but I wasn't sure how often the deleted file's timestamp would just happen to be equal to the counter. Is there any easy way to prevent this, or would it be so unlikely that I shouldn't be concerned? Anyway, it would be ideal if I could just use getModificationStamp().
BTW, using a single method would be a decent performance gain for WTP too. I've found that using both is relatively slow for large workspaces, since it involves a lot of file access.

I'll consider this as an enhancement request to change modification stamp to avoid this problem on recreate. In the meantime, adding the mod stamp and the local time stamp should give you the behaviour you need.
Both getModificationStamp and getLocalTimeStamp are only tree lookups in our workspace, so they should be very fast. We also cache the most recent lookup, so two calls should have about the same cost as one. If you had an experience with slow local timestamp access, it might have been prior to Eclipse 3.0. In Eclipse 3.0 we added API to access the cached local timestamp, which is 30x faster than going to the disk (see bug 39492). Hopefully you're already using this fast method ;)

Thanks John, that'll solve my problem.
The "slow" access was on v3.2, but that was a 'relative' statement since we were testing on workspaces with 24K+ files and calling it multiple times per file :). I'll double-check and open up another bug if anything seems out of order.

bug.short_desc: [Undo] [IDE] - Undoing a resource delete does not restore session and persistent properties

long_desc.thetext:
When a resource is deleted, the DeleteResourcesOperation stores a description of the resource so it can be later restored. There is currently no way in the IResource API to enumerage what session and persistent properties are available, so that they can be remembered and restored.
Further, it's not clear whether this is a good idea, since these arbitrary properties could be large.
What is the best strategy?

Discussed this with JohnA, who suggests:
>I'm not sure if it's necessary to incorporate this information into >undo/redo. The kind of information stored in these properties typically >isn't information that the user has any way of knowing about - it's just >arbitrary metadata associated with the resource that we're holding on behalf >on some plugin. Typically this is cache-like information that can be >recomputed if it's lost. I'd suggest leaving this out for now and see if it >becomes an issue.
This may not be a priority for 3.3, but marking 3.3 for now so that any remaining limitations of the new workspace undo support can be examined and documented.

There is a minor flaw with source control systems which may be related to this bug: - Choose a file that is under source control - Delete it - Restore the file from local history
The source control doesn't consider the file as unchanged as it is (it was deleted and the deletion was reverted). - The eclipse CVS shows the file as modified but there is no difference - Subclipse shows the file as deleted

The scenario in comment #3 is not related to this bug, as it refers to restoring a file manually from local history. If you a delete a file under CVS control and select "Edit>Undo Delete Resources" the file is restored and CVS does not mark the file as modified.
Marking this bug as WONTFIX since there is no compelling case to address it.

bug.short_desc: [Viewers] TreeViewer does not populate root/input children

long_desc.thetext:
The same behavior as described in bug#156537 but with release M20060921-0945 (3.2.1)
TreeViewer created with SWT.VIRTUAL flag and set to use ILazyTreeContentProvider does not populate root/input children if "TreeViewer.setChildCount" or "TreeViewer.refresh" is not called after "TreeViewer.setInput" is called. The right behavior would be TreeView to call "ILazyTreeContentProvider.updateChildCount" as it is documented (see ILazyTreeContentProvider#updateChildCount method documentation).
Consider for 3.2.2.

Looking at this again it doesn't seem critical enough to fix in 3.2.2.
You describe an easy and safe workaround, and the workaround will not cause problems when upgrading to 3.3.

First of all it is inconsistent Eclipse 3.2 API behavior. You could fix it in Eclipse 3.3 by just changing documentation, but you should fix it in Eclipse 3.2 by changing the implementation.
I think that it is very important to community to have stable API. So... lets sees the impact of this bug. As workaround there are to possibilities:
- call refresh immediately after input was setted - commonly usage of ILazyTreeContentProvider is when querying underling models is expensive, in such case it is really bad idea to call refresh without it is needed. - call setChildCount immediately - it is supposed this to be done by content provider just because it is supposed to know hot to query the model for that.
It is obvious that not closing this bug you are forcing a lot of bad implementations till Eclipse 3.3 is released, which means at least half a year of bad implementations.

Our policy for point releases is to only put in safe fixes for critical issues. This is because they are not subject as much testing as a regular release. A critical issue is one that causes data loss or crashes, or prevents shipping a product.
BTW, the implementation of TreeViewer has already been fixed in 3.3. I should also mention that there were some other bugs in TrreViewer's VIRTUAL support that surfaced after 3.2 shipped and were only fixed in the 3.3 stream.

bug.short_desc: [jsr269] Need interfaces between jdt compiler and jsr269 impl

long_desc.thetext:
We need interfaces between the JDT batch compiler and the JSR269 implementation in o.e.jdt.compiler.apt. This bug is a forum for discussion.
At present, o.e.jdt.internal.compiler.batch.Main supports command line invocation by parsing the command line and then constructing and invoking an o.e.jdt.internal.compiler.Compiler. The JSR199 implementation works by extending Main to implement the new javax.tools.JavaCompiler interface.
To add APT support, APT will subclass o.e.jdt.internal.compiler.Compiler. The subclass will be named o.e.jdt.compiler.apt.internal.AptCompiler. Instead of just instantiating a new Compiler, the command-line and JSR199 batch compiler invocations will need to either create a Compiler if annotation processing is not required, or gets a Compiler from APT via reflection if it is.
Note that according to the Java documentation, javac defaults to running annotation processors unless the -noproc option is explicitly specified. If no -processors or -processorPath option is explicitly specified, it searches the classpath to find processors. So we cannot rely on the presence of these options to indicate the need for annotation processing. This suggests that, to decide whether to instantiate the Compiler from APT or from JDT, we would need to not only look at the command line options but also (in the default case) crack every jar on the classpath and look at the files in its META-INF/services folder to see if it offers a Processor. Whether that's the right thing to do, or whether we should deviate from the javac spec to be more efficient, is Philippe's call, I think.
To support the JSR199 CompilationTask.setProcessors() method, Compiler will need an additional setProcessors() method itself; on the JDT Compiler this will be implemented with UnsupportedOperationException but in APT it will actually set processors.
In batch mode, AptCompiler needs a filesystem proxy to read files (e.g. processor jars) and create resource files and Java source files. This could be a JavaFileManager, except that's a JSR199 class and thus not available within base JDT. It needs to have most or all of the functionality of JavaFileManager; in particular it needs to be able to honor getFileAsInput(StandardLocation.ANNOTATION_PROCESSOR_PATH, ...) and getJavaFileAsOutput(StandardLocation.SOURCE_OUTPUT, ...) based on the -processorPath and -s options of the command line, or else it needs to provide broad enough filesystem access to let the APT command-line code implement that functionality. In the JSR199 invocation case, callers can pass in their own JavaFileManager, which must then be passed to APT.
APT also needs access to additional command line options: -A, -processorPath, -processor, -proc:only, -s, -XprintProcessorInfo, and -XprintRounds.
I suggest that JDT create an interface CompilerFactory, which would be implemented by APT as a singleton object AptBatchCompilerFactory obtained through reflection, and which would have one method, newCompiler( existing Compiler constructor params, plus filesystem proxy ).
In IDE mode, Compiler is created by AbstractImageBuilder. Here again, this needs to create an AptCompiler instead if annotation processing is required. However, the processing context mostly comes from the platform (reading preferences, loading processors from plug-ins, etc.) rather than being passed in. This object needs to be created via the extension mechanism, rather than reflection. So I suggest an extension point o.e.jdt.core.extendedCompiler, whose implementation interface is CompilerFactory. In the IDE, AbstractImageBuilder would use this extension point to get an AptIdeCompilerFactory from APT. This version of CompilerFactory would ignore the filesystem proxy and the extended options, instead getting them from the platform.

We propose the following ideas: 1) If a processor is detected (this will need to be clarified), we would insert a loop after the actual beginToCompile(...) call and before the process units. This loop would call a ProcessorManager (or another name like that). The processor manager would know how to process the known units and collects the new units created while processing them. If new units have been created, the lookup environment would be reset and the beginToCompile loop called again with old units and new units. Once the second beginToCompile is done, the ProcessorManager would not be called again. I believe we agreed that the creation of the new units is done in one pass.
Any thoughts?
I said that we need to clarify how a processor is detected. I guess we can do it by processing the different apt options. I need to get information on them in order to know what they should do.
Do you see any missing part in this compilation loop?
ProcessorManager --> AnnotationProcessorManager #process(...) --> #processAnnotations(...)

Olivier asked: > What kind of information do you need to "process" the > annotations of the units? > I have read that as soon as each annotation has a "matching" > processor, there is no more lookup for processors. Will you > take care of that part inside the apt code?
Mainly, in addition to the annotated units themselves, what we need is the information necessary to discover and load processors. And, as noted above, we need access to a filesystem, such as what JavaFileManager provides.
From the command-line entry point, if there is a -processorPath option, or -processor options, we need those; if not, we need the -classpath and (if it already exists and is convenient) a classloader for it.
If the JSR199 entry point is being used, it seems more involved. Some aspects of JSR199 that I don't understand include:
- JavaCompiler.getTask() takes as an argument "Iterable<String> classes". The javadoc says "class names (for annotation processing)" but I have no idea what that's supposed to mean, nor what classloader is supposed to be used to load these classes. It does not seem to correspond to any javac command line option.
- ToolProvider.getSystemClassLoader() is supposed to return "the class loader for tools provided with this platform". I don't think that classloader needs to be able to load processor classes, but I'm not sure. If it does, that implies that either JDT needs to create the processor class loader, or else APT needs to be able to create it and then hand it back to JDT on demand.
- JavaFileManager.getClassLoader() is supposed to be able to provide a class loader for, among other things, annotation processors. Since the caller can specify a JavaFileManager in their call to JavaCompiler.getTask(), I assume that we are supposed to use that class loader to load our annotation processors. I guess that in javac, they have a command-line option parser that creates a JavaFileManager that includes a class loader based on the -classpath or-processorPath option, and then the compiler calls that method to load its annotation processors. I assume the idea is that from the JSR199 entry point, if CompilationTask.setProcessors() has been called then the JFM classloader will not be used; and that at the command line, if -processor options are detected, they translate into calls to CompilationTask.setProcessors().
So, taking those things into account, one possibility is for you guys to provide us (regardless of whether the entry point is command line or JSR199) with a JavaFileManager that has a class loader that honors the Location switch and that includes the annotation processor path. However, that still leaves open the question of how APT is supposed to actually *discover* the processors on that classpath. Possibly the answer is for JDT to implement java.util.ServiceLoader. (Or APT could implement it; but to do that we will need to look at the manifests of all the jars on the processor classpath and/or factory classpath, which might be duplicated effort.)
I think there is a lot there that might be unnecessary for users - I don't know whether it will be part of the Sun JCK, though.
As mentioned above, APT also needs access to some additional command line options: -A, -proc:only, -s, -XprintProcessorInfo, and -XprintRounds, or the corresponding options from the JSR199 mechanism.

This adds the looping strategy, but we would still need a good way to initialize the annotation processor manager. Walter, I think we should talk together about a good way to process the command line and add new options.

First, let's talk about the local case:
The bottle neck in this case is in the for loop of SystemZipHandler#recreateZipRenameEntries(), since in a big zip file, the list of virtual children could be very big. This is the callstack portion:
ZipOutputStream.write(byte[], int, int) line: not available SystemZipHandler.recreateZipRenameEntries(VirtualChild[], ZipOutputStream, HashMap) line: 1094 SystemZipHandler.fullRename(String, String, boolean) line: 1548 SystemZipHandler.fullRename(String, String) line: 1483 SystemZipHandler.rename(String, String) line: 1599 LocalFileService.renameVirtualFile(File, String) line: 1035 LocalFileService.rename(String, String, String, IProgressMonitor) line: 998 FileServiceSubSystem.rename(IRemoteFile, String, IProgressMonitor) line: 606 SystemViewRemoteFileAdapter$RenameJob.run(IProgressMonitor) line: 1737
As you can see, the IProgressMonitor is only available up to LocalFileService.rename().
I remembered we discussed briefly about what is the machenism of communicate the SystemZipHandler, but did not seem able to find the note for it (either from the meeting note or from the bug report). I remembered that we agreed with a polling on a separate thread for the IProgressMontior status. But not sure how can we communicate the polling result to the correpsonding method in SystemZipHandler. The only way I could think of now is to construct an special status object in probably LocalFileServer#rename() method, and pass it all the way to the corresponding methods in SytemZipHandler. But that requires quite a lot of API changes (since there are other operations, move, delete, etc, need to be considered).

For archive APIs, it is very common that one archive API calls to a different API, and both of them need to open the archive file. For example, SystemZipHandler#getVirtualChildrenList() could be called by SystemZipHandler#fullRename(), SystemZipHandler#add(), SystemZipHandler#delete(). And it could also be called by UniversalFileTransferUtility#compressedCopyRemoteResourceToWorkspace().
So I need a mutex class which makes sure the waitForLock() method will not wait if the thread of current request of lock is the same as the thread which holding the lock currently.
For example, SystemZipHandler#fullRename() calls waitForLock() and acquired the lock. Then it calls SystemZipHandler#getVirtualChildrenList() as part of its rename operation. And the code of SystemZipHandler#getVirtualChildrenList() also calls waitForLock(). And at this moment, the lock is held by the thread of the SystemZipHandler#fullRename(). Since the thread where SystemZipHandler#getVirtualChildrenList() is running is of the same thread, the waitForLock() call invoked by SystemZipHandler#getVirtualChildrenList() will "borrow" the lock, so that it will not be blocked. This way, we could make sure once the lock is acquired by one thread, the sequencial operations in the same thread will be executed as one unit. The lock is released only if the waitForLock() method actually acquires the lock (the situation in SystemZipHandler#fullRename() in the example), instead of "borrowing" the lock (the situation in SystemZipHandler#getVirtualChildrenList() in the example).

I fully agree that all RSE jobs should be cancelable.
The problem is, that it's up to the subsystems / service implementations to make service requests cancelable. Sometimes this may be pretty hard, since a "fetch directory contents" query on the local system is an OS operation, that is not easy to cancel itself (needs to run in a separate thread which is then interrupted by another thread).
I think that 1.) At least some RSE subsystems should be fully cancelable, to provide a "reference implementation" for our users. I'd suggest the Local and SSH subsystems since they are considerably simpler than dstore. 2.) The RSE Framework must not prevent subsystems from being fully cancelable. By doing reference implementations, we'll be able to verify that. 3.) The RSE Framework should provide some helper classes that makes it easier for service implementors to create cancelable implementations.
It might also be possible that the framework destroys threads / jobs in order to cancel them, but I do not think that's a good idea since it might lead to cleanup problems.
With respect to the "collapsing a node should cancel" I'm also not sure that's a good idea. The main mechanism for canceling jobs should be the progress view. After all it's a background job going on, so it should not hurt the user. Does anybody know if there are Eclipse UI guidelines for this?

Any fix in documentation is high priority for 1.0.1 -- please consider for 1.0.1 to get the docs in sync with the code again.
Documentation and references in the code have been updated to refer to the "Remote Shell" view.

I'm not 100% happy yet with the fix for the following reasons:
* All user-visible strings now refer to "Remote Shell", but in the code we still have many constants like RESID_COMMANDSVIEW_* REMOTE_COMMANDS_VIEW_* COMMANDS_VIEW_ID EVENT_COMMAND_* ACTION_COMMANDSVIEW_* TYPE_COMMAND there seems to be some inconsistency here, which it looks like we'll not be able to do away easily since the constants are (partially) API
* The RSE "Remote Shell" view is totally line-oriented. It is good for running commands with line-oriented output. In my opinion, it does not qualify as a full-featured interactive shell, but it is much more a remote commands view. Especially, when we are going to get the Terminal view (which can then be used as a view into a remote shell), this distinction will be even more important.
* The RSE "Remote Shell" view can also be used to view the output of not-user-initiated commands (through the IRemoteCommandShell interface).
Perhaps it would have been better to rename all occurrences of "Remote Shell" to "Remote Command" instead. We should discuss this once again.

I'm willing to change this back to Remote Commands everywhere instead of Remote Shell. This isn't a shell in the normal sense and Remote Commands seems to capture the spirit of the beast a little better.
Moving to release 2.0 for this change.
Comments?
Moving to future. While not a large change there are a fair number of ripples. We need to poll on this and make the change early in the next release.

bug.short_desc: The elements in ecore editor can't move

long_desc.thetext: Create an example of ecore diagram, add two EClass into the editor, right click the tab and select 'New Editor' in the popup menu, then a new editor is open, close the new opened editor, and drag the EClass in the original editor, the EClass can't move.
We need to see if this is a regression from GMF 1.0.

I think the problem comes from the generated ecore diagram editor code. The ecore diagram editor creates new document provider (EcoreDocumentProvider) each time new editor is being created. Hence, when the editor is closed the document provider is diposed, because only one editor input is connected to it (the new one is created for new editor's inputs). If document provider is diposed the model resource is unloaded, consequently if two editors are opened for the same model closing one editor will result in unloading resource and therefore the second editor can't edit or save the diagram due to the null resource.
Instead of creating document providers per new editors, the non-generated exampes (Logic editor) use the already existing document providers stored in the providers registry and hence for the second editor opened the document provider is the same as for the first one, hence it can keep track of the number of client editors working on the same editor input (resource). The document provider is diposed only if this number becomes 0, i.e. no editors opened for the same input. I think the same logic should be used for the generated editors.

Created an attachment (id=52160) patch for the generated code
Here is a patch for the generated ecore diagram editor
Instead of creating new document providers (EcoreDocumentProvider) per new ecore diagram editors, we'll try to use the same instance which will be stored in the document providers registry. Hence method getDocumentProvider(IEditorInput input) shouldn't be overriden (the StorageDiagramDocumentProvider should be returned for non IFile inputs from org.eclipse.gmf.runtime.diagram.ui.resources.editor.ide plugin). This will allow editor to grab the proper document provider from the registry if there it exists there.
To have document provider (EcoreDocumentProvider) for ecore diagram editor in the document providers registry it's added in the plugin file through org.eclipse.gmf.runtime.diagram.ui.resources.editor.documentProviders extension to be able to use this document provider for "ecore_diagram" file editor inputs

Created an attachment (id=52164) patch for the runtime diagram
Here is a little improvement patch for the runtime diagram side.
matches(IEditorReference editorRef, IEditorInput input) method was obtaining the document provider for the instance of DiagramDocumentEditor ignoring the method getDocumentProvider() defined in DiagramDocumentEditor, which could be overriden by clients. The fix is use this method instead. (Before it was a copy-pasted chunk of code from DiagramDocumentEditor.getDocumentProvider()
Alex, could you please verify if this is indeed the generated editor code issue?

Hi, Alex! My questions are: 1. Why DiagramIOUtil.unload(((IDiagramDocument)info.fDocument).getEditingDomain(), (Diagram)content); called in FileDiagramDocumentProvider.disposeElementInfo()? Looks like all the unnecessary objects would be automatically removed by garbage-collector in thiscase. 2. What about StorageDiagramDocumentProvider conditionally created in EcoreDiagramEditor now? Currently corresponding piece of runtime was not modified 3. Current version of EcoreDiagramEditor create statefull instance of EcoreDocumentProvider (check the latest sources) so it can not be easily substituted by shared instance from registry. We are going to review this place and create some other solution for it (probably use different IEditorInput subclass). This was invented to correctly open several diagrams stored in the same diagram file.

Hi Alex,
First of all, I was obviously not aware of the reasons you mentioned above... so my patch is most likely useless. I've tried to answer your questions though.
1) Doesn't look like eobjects contained by the resource will be garbage collected. First of all resource is not removed from the resource set, it stays there (although I didn't see an explicit reason why it's not removed, perhaps it should be). Hence, if list of contents (eobjects) owned by the resource is not cleared eobjects will stay in memory. Second, Eclipse's navigational history holds onto editor input when editor is opened and then closed. Editor input holds onto editing domain, which holds onto resource set. Third, when resource is unloaded, i.e. list of contents is cleared, the cross reference adapter (ECrossReferenceAdapter) is notified that the following resource is unloaded and moves resource in the hash of unloaded resources. Also, since we use a GMFResource, the doUnload method from XMLResourceImpl clears up 3 maps ids -> eobjects, eobjects - > ids and eobjects - > extension maps.
2) I was thinking that StorageDiagramDocumentProvider resides in the registry, coming in via org.eclipse.gmf.runtime.diagram.ui.resources.editor.ide plugin. It should be provided for IStorageEditorInput inputs. This should be ok, unless StorageDiagramDocumentProvider is used for other editor inputs.
3) Since we'd better not have EcoreDocumentProvider in the registry, perhaps we could count number of editors opened for the same resource as it's done in the AbstractDocumentProvider through the fElementInfoMap map in EcoreDocumentProvider but using a static map? or perhaps even use a static fElementInfoMap map somewhere in the upper layers, maybe even in AbstractDocumentProvider class (not sure if it's a safe thing to do)?
Any thoughts at all how to go about this issue?

bug.short_desc: The CDT jni libraries on OS X are PPC only. They need to be Universal Binary.

long_desc.thetext:
The CDT ships with only PPC jni libraries. Universal binary versions need to be built. This means changing the Makefile to create universal Binary libraries. Here is the new Makefile that accomplishes this goal.
# makefile for libspawner.so # See http://developer.apple.com/documentation/Java/Conceptual/Java141Development/Core_APIs/chapter_6_section_4.html
JAVA_HOME = /Library/Java/Home ifeq ($(JAVA_HOME),) $(warning JAVA_HOME not set in environment) endif
# Defaults which can be overridden. OS = macosx ARCH = Universal SYS_ROOT=/Developer/SDKs/MacOSX10.4u.sdk JDK_INCLUDES= $(SYS_ROOT)/System/Library/Frameworks/JavaVM.framework/Headers
CC=gcc LD=libtool CPPFLAGS = -I. -I$(JDK_INCLUDES) CFLAGS +=-fPIC -D_REENTRANT -O -g \ -isysroot $(SYS_ROOT) -arch i386 -arch ppc LDFLAGS=-arch ppc -arch i386 -isysroot $(SYS_ROOT)
INSTALL_DIR = ../os/$(OS)/$(ARCH)
LIB_NAME_SPAWNER = libspawner.dylib LIB_NAME_FULL_SPAWNER = $(INSTALL_DIR)/libspawner.jnilib OBJS_SPAWNER=spawner.o io.o exec_unix.o exec_pty.o openpty.o pfind.o
LIB_NAME_PTY = libpty.so LIB_NAME_FULL_PTY = $(INSTALL_DIR)/libpty.jnilib OBJS_PTY= openpty.o pty.o ptyio.o
OBJS = $(OBJS_SPAWNER) $(OBJS_PTY)
all: $(LIB_NAME_FULL_SPAWNER) $(LIB_NAME_FULL_PTY)
rebuild: clean all
$(LIB_NAME_FULL_SPAWNER) : $(OBJS_SPAWNER) mkdir -p $(INSTALL_DIR) $(CC) -dynamiclib -o $(LIB_NAME_FULL_SPAWNER) $(OBJS_SPAWNER) -lc -framework JavaVM $(LDFLAGS)
$(LIB_NAME_FULL_PTY): $(OBJS_PTY) mkdir -p $(INSTALL_DIR) $(CC) -dynamiclib -o $(LIB_NAME_FULL_PTY) $(OBJS_PTY) -lc -framework JavaVM $(LDFLAGS)
clean : $(RM) $(OBJS_SPAWNER) $(LIB_NAME_FULL_SPAWNER) $(RM) $(OBJS_PTY) $(LIB_NAME_FULL_PTY)

Would be great to get the full support of the new Intel Macs...
